-- PRESS DIGEST-New Zealand newspapers - July 3
-- 
-- Wed Jul 02, 2014 03:52PM EDT
-- None



WELLINGTON, July 3 (Reuters) - Following are some of the lead stories from New Zealand metropolitan newspapers on Thursday.

Stories may be taken from either the paper or Internet editions of the papers. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.  DOMINION POST(www.stuff.co.nz) TTR to fight decision on sand-mining: The Trans-Tasman Resources (TTR) board will appeal against the Environmental Protection Authority's (EPA) decision to decline its marine consents for mining iron sands off the South Taranaki coast. - - - - $50m lolly dangled by Labour: Parents unable to afford their children's school donations would get a reprieve under a Labour initiative to scrap donations and replace them with an annual government grant. - - - - Vets ready to deal with foot-and-mouth: New Zealand veterinarians and officials are better prepared for an outbreak of foot-and-mouth disease, following a visit to Nepal to see the problem first-hand. - - - -   NEW ZEALAND HERALD (www.nzherald.co.nz) Ministry boss offers to resign: Ministry of Foreign Affairs head John Allen offered to resign over his ministry's mishandling of the case of a Malaysian diplomat who left the country after an alleged attempt to rape a Wellington woman. - - - - UK rip-off riles honey firms: Manuka honey exporters want the Government to clamp down on "cowboys" bringing the NZ$150 million-a-year industry into international disrepute. - - - - Drop in milk price sets off ripples: Fonterra's <FSF.NZ> $7 per kg farmgate milk price forecast for 2014/15 is once again under significant downward pressure because of ongoing falls in international dairy prices and a stubbornly high New Zealand dollar, say economists. - - - - Tourism Holdings upbeat on profit: Tourism Holdings' <THL.NZ> share price jumped 6 per cent yesterday after the company said its profit this year may beat guidance released earlier this year. - - - -